text: Simplify label loading
Fixed in f3b86be
Why is resume off by default?
Same remark here (and everywhere with resume): is there a reason not to turn on resume by default?
Looks like there is some old code lying here.
That doesn't make sens: md5sums is None, and you cannot test 'in' for None. As a result the tests do not pass in your branch.
As a general remark, I'd like _every_ object that is a nimg-like to be named foo_img. In my experience such naming conventions are very useful, both for the user and the developer.
Actually, it does not work for you because you are using a cutting edge scikit-learn (the commit 40328ed685be70d0ebdabecd65c6d85c5b55e85c fixes a bug in scikit-learn pipeline). I will fix this.

I added the resume feature because I had huge problems downloadiing the ADHD dataset. Problem is that the resume feature has not been fully tested for the moment and may lead to unexpected results so I have chosen to keep it disabled for the moment. Plus, if we decide to enable it by default later, I think that this won't disturb the user.
I don't understand: this fails on my computer because "FastICA has no attribute 'inverse_transform'". Does it work on your computer @AlexandreAbraham ? We need to fix this.

Random notes as I go:
- I don't like the name 'compute_session_epi_mask'. I know that it is what is used in nipy, but I don't like it
- I don't like the name 'regressor' in the datasets, do designate confound regressors. I think that I'd rather have them be called 'confounds'.
